04097nam a22005415i 9780774850209DE-B159720240306124542.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240306t20072002xxc    fo  d z      eng d  a97807748502097 a10.59962/97807748502092doi  a(DE-B1597)661716  a(OCoLC)951200098  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  axxccCA 4aF1039.5.H17 ǂb A76 2002eb 7aHIS0270002bisacsh04a940.4/571 aArmstrong, John Griffith, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut14aThe Halifax Explosion and the Royal Canadian Navy :bInquiry and Intrigue /cJohn Griffith Armstrong. 1aVancouver ;aToronto : bUniversity of British Columbia Press, c[2007] 4c©2002  a1 online resource (256 p.) :b16 b&w photographs, 3 maps  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aStudies in Canadian Military History00tFront Matter -- tContents -- tIllustrations -- tForeword -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction: Through Sailors’ Eyes -- tThe Royal Canadian Navy in Halifax – December 1917 -- tTowards the Unthinkable -- tHalifax Tide -- tThrough the Grim Day -- tReaction and Recovery -- tOf Sailors, Lawyers, Goats, and Newspapers -- tGoats to the Slaughter -- tCovering the Tracks -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe Halifax Explosion of 1917 is a defining event in the Canadian consciousness, yet it has never been the subject of a sustained analytical history. Astonishingly, until now no one has consulted the large federal government archives that contain first-hand accounts of the disaster and the response of national authorities. Canada's recently established navy was at the epicentre of the crisis. Armstrong reveals the navy's compelling, and little-known, story by carefully retracing the events preceding the disaster and the role of the military in its aftermath. He catches the pulse of disaster response in official Ottawa and provides a compelling analysis of the legal manoeuvres, rhetoric, blunders, public controversy, and crisis management that ensued. His disturbing conclusion is that federal officials knew of potential dangers in the harbour before the explosion, took no corrective action, and kept the information from the public. As a result, a Halifax naval officer was made a scapegoat and the navy received lasting, and mostly undeserved, vilification. This is a provocative read not only for military and naval devotees but for anyone who wants to understand one of the events that shaped Canada in the twentieth century.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 7aHISTORY / Military / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Complete eBook-Package Pre-2010z978311127416408iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Upgrade eBook-Package pre 2010z978311127724008iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of British Columbia eBook-Package 2013-2000z978311141860540uhttps://doi.org/10.59962/978077485020940uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780774850209423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780774850209/original  a978-3-11-127416-4  ACUP Complete eBook-Package Pre-2010b2010  a978-3-11-127724-0  ACUP Upgrade eBook-Package pre 2010b2010  a978-3-11-141860-5  University of British Columbia eBook-Package 2013-2000c2013d2000  aGBV-deGruyter-alles